The DL1r NN has a multidimensional output corresponding to the probabilities for a jet to be a
				b-jet, a
				c-jet or a light-flavour jet. The use of a multi-class network architecture provides the algorithm with a smaller memory footprint than the previous ATLAS MV2c10 algorithm [
				6] based on boosted decision trees (BDTs). The topology of the network consists of a mixture of fully connected hidden layers. The DL1r algorithm parameters, listed in Table
				2, include the architecture of the NN, the number of training epochs, the learning rates and training batch size. Each of these parameters is optimised in order to maximise the




								b
								-tagging


